natural problem: The function $f$ has the property that, for each real number $x$, \[f(x) + f(x-1) = x^2.\]If $f(19) = 94$, what is $f(94)$?

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x :: real and f :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. f x + f (x-1) = x powr 2"
and h1 : "f 19 = 94"
shows  "f 94 = 4561"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 The function $f$ has the property that, for each real number $x$, \[f(x) + f(x-1) = x^2.\]If $f(19) = 94$, what is $f(94)$? The final Answer is 4561
 ### Proof
 We compute directly using the given recursive definition: \[\begin{aligned} f(94) &= 94^2 - f(93) \\ &= 94^2 - 93^2 + f(92) \\ &= 94^2 - 93^2 + 92^2 - f(91) \\ &= \dotsb \\ &= 94^2 - 93^2 + 92^2 - 91^2 + \cdots + 20^2 - f(19) \\ &= (94^2 - 93^2 + 92^2 - 91^2 + \cdots + 20^2) - 94.
 \end{aligned}\]To compute this sum, we write \[\begin{aligned} 94^2 - 93^2 + 92^2 - 91^2 + \dots + 20^2& = (94^2 - 93^2) + (92^2 - 91^2) + \dots + (22^2 - 21^2) + 20^2 \\ &= (94 + 93) + (92 + 91) + \dots + (22 + 21) + 20^2 \\ &= \frac{1}{2}(94+21)(94-21+1) + 400 \\ &= 4255 + 400 \\ &= 4655.
 \end{aligned}\]Therefore, \[f(94) = 4655 - 94 = \boxed{4561}.\]
 *)
